@{
    Layout = null;
}
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>MediBridge - Water Purification</title>

    <!-- Tailwind CSS -->
    <script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"></script>
    <script>
        tailwind.config = {
            theme: {
                extend: {
                    colors: {
                        primary: '#3B82F6',
                        secondary: '#10B981',
                    },
                },
            },
        };
    </script>

    <!-- Hide Scrollbar -->
    <style>
        html, body {
            scrollbar-width: none;
            -ms-overflow-style: none;
        }

            html::-webkit-scrollbar,
            body::-webkit-scrollbar {
                display: none;
            }
    </style>
</head>
<body class="bg-white text-gray-800 font-sans">
    <main class="max-w-5xl mx-auto p-6 text-justify space-y-10">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-800 mb-6">Chemical Disinfection of Water</h1>

        <p class="mb-4">You can kill most germs in water with chemical disinfectants such as:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-700">
            <li><strong>Unscented household chlorine bleach</strong></li>
            <li><strong>Iodine</strong></li>
            <li><strong>Chlorine dioxide tablets</strong></li>
        </ul>

        <div class="bg-yellow-100 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 text-yellow-700 p-4 mb-6">
            <p>Note: Chemical disinfectants are less effective than boiling at killing some parasites, including <strong>Cryptosporidium</strong> and <strong>Giardia</strong>.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-700 mb-4">Steps to Disinfect Water Using Bleach</h2>
        <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 text-gray-800 mb-6 space-y-2">
            <li>If water is cloudy, filter it first using a clean cloth, paper towel, or coffee filter. Let it settle if necessary.</li>
            <li>Use the bleach concentration table below to determine the correct amount.</li>
            <li>Stir the bleach and water mixture well.</li>
            <li>Let the water stand for at least 30 minutes before drinking.</li>
            <li>Store disinfected water in clean, sanitized, tightly covered containers.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="mb-6">
            <img src="~/Images/chemical/bleach.png" alt="Illustration of dropper adding bleach" class="w-auto h-[60vh] mx-auto">
        </div>


        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-blue-700 mb-2">Bleach (5%–9% Sodium Hypochlorite)</h2>
        <p class="mb-4">If water is cloudy, murky, colored, or cold — double the dosage.</p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
            <table class="min-w-full table-auto border border-gray-300 text-sm">
                <thead class="bg-gray-200 text-gray-800">
                    <tr>
                        <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Water Amount</th>
                        <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Dropper</th>
                        <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Milliliters (mL)</th>
                        <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Measuring Spoon</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="bg-white text-gray-700">
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">1 quart / liter</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">2 drops</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">0.1 mL</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">Tiny amount (too small to measure)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">1 gallon</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">8 drops</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">0.5 mL</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">Just under ⅛ tsp</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">5 gallons</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">40 drops</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">2.5 mL</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">½ tsp</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-blue-700 mb-2">Bleach (1% Sodium Hypochlorite)</h2>
        <p class="mb-4">Double the amount for cloudy, murky, or very cold water.</p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
            <table class="min-w-full table-auto border border-gray-300 text-sm">
                <thead class="bg-gray-200 text-gray-800">
                    <tr>
                        <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Water Amount</th>
                        <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Dropper</th>
                        <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Milliliters (mL)</th>
                        <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Measuring Spoon</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="bg-white text-gray-700">
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">1 quart / liter</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">10 drops</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">0.5 mL</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">⅛ tsp</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">1 gallon</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">40 drops</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">2.5 mL</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">½ tsp</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">5 gallons</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">200 drops</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">12.5 mL</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-2">2½ tsp</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>

        <div class="mb-8 text-center">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Chemical Illustrations</h2>

            <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4 items-center">
                <!-- Bleach -->
                <div class="flex flex-col items-center justify-center">
                    <img src="~/Images/chemical/bleach.png" alt="Illustration of bleach" class="w-auto h-[40vh] object-contain">
                    <p class="text-sm font-medium mt-2">Bleach (Sodium Hypochlorite)</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Chlorine -->
                <div class="flex flex-col items-center justify-center ">
                    <img src="~/Images/chemical/chlorine.png" alt="Illustration of chlorine" class="w-auto h-[40vh] p-8 object-contain">
                    <p class="text-sm font-medium mt-2">Chlorine Dioxide</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Iodine -->
                <div class="flex flex-col items-center justify-center">
                    <img src="~/Images/chemical/Iodine.png" alt="Illustration of iodine" class="w-auto h-[40vh] object-contain">
                    <p class="text-sm font-medium mt-2">Iodine Solution</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex items-center text-justify ">
            <div class=" p-6 w-2/3 mx-auto">
                <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4"> Using Chlorine Dioxide Drops</h2>
                <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-left text-gray-800">
                    <li>
                        <strong>Mix the Drops:</strong>
                        <p class="ml-4">
                            Mix equal drops of Part A and Part B in a small, dry container (e.g., 2 drops of each).
                            Let the mixture sit for <strong>30 seconds to 1 minute</strong> to activate (it will turn yellowish).
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <strong>Add to Water:</strong>
                        <p class="ml-4">
                            Add the activated mixture to <strong>1 liter of water</strong>.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <strong>Shake and Wait:</strong>
                        <p class="ml-4">
                            Shake or stir well.<br>
                            Wait <strong>15–30 minutes</strong> before drinking.<br>
                            Extend to <strong>4 hours</strong> for very dirty or cold water.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </div>

            <div class="flex flex-col items-center justify-center w-1/3">
                <img src="~/Images/chemical/chlorine.png" alt="Illustration of chlorine" class="w-auto h-[40vh] p-10 object-contain">
                <p class="text-sm font-medium mt-2">Chlorine Dioxide</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex items-center text-justify ">
            <div class=" p-6 w-2/3 mx-auto">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6 text-center tracking-tighter">How to Purify Water with Iodine Solution</h2>

                <div class="space-y-6">
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Step 1: Prepare the Water</h3>
                        <p>
                            If the water is cloudy or contains particles, strain it through a cloth or coffee filter to remove sediment. This helps improve the effectiveness of the iodine treatment.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Step 2: Add Iodine and Mix</h3>
                        <p>
                            Add 5 drops of 2% tincture of iodine per liter (or quart) of clear water. For cloudy water, increase the dose to 10 drops per liter. Stir or shake the water well to distribute the iodine evenly.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Step 3: Wait and Drink</h3>
                        <p>
                            Let the water sit for at least 30 minutes to allow the iodine to disinfect it properly. If the water is cold (below 5°C or 41°F), extend the wait time to one hour. After this period, the water should be safe to drink. Note that iodine-treated water may taste strong, which can be improved by adding vitamin C after purification if desired. Avoid long-term use, especially if pregnant or having thyroid issues.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="flex flex-col items-center justify-center w-1/3">
                <img src="~/Images/chemical/Iodine.png" alt="Illustration of iodine" class="w-auto h-[40vh] object-contain">
                <p class="text-sm font-medium mt-2">Iodine Solution</p>
            </div>
        </div>


        <div class="bg-red-100 border-l-4 border-red-500 text-red-700 p-4 mb-6">
            <p><strong>Warning:</strong> Iodine and chlorine do <u>not</u> kill <strong>Cryptosporidium</strong>. Only properly used <strong>chlorine dioxide tablets</strong> are effective against it.</p>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">Who Should Avoid Iodine-Treated Water</h3>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 mb-6">
            <li>Pregnant individuals</li>
            <li>People with thyroid problems</li>
            <li>Anyone with hypersensitivity to iodine</li>
            <li>Do not use iodine-treated water for more than a few weeks</li>
        </ul>

        @* <div class="mb-6">
            <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x200?text=Chlorine+Dioxide+and+Iodine+Tablets" alt="Illustration of chemical disinfection tablets" class="rounded shadow">
        </div> *@
    </main>
</body>
</html>
